<td><div>
      
<font size="+3" color=#990000>In English</font><font size="+3"> you say <font size="+4" color="#EE871B">"a book" </font>
when speaking about a single book, but when you talk about several books you can't say 
<font size="+4" color="#EE871B">"a books" </font>, right?  You need to switch the 
<font size="+4" color="#EE871B">"a" </font> for <font size="+4" color="#EE871B">"some"</font> and say 
<font size="+4" color="#EE871B">"some books"</font>.<br><br>

You already knew this, but do you know why?<br><br>

Well, "book" being singular, can only go with "a", which is also singular, and 
"books" being plural, can only go with "some", which is also plural.  
<br><br>

This pattern of matching the two words is called 
<font size="+4" color="#EE871B">agreement</font> because they agree with each other.

</font>
<font size="3" color="#5E00FF"><a href="gender_4.html">Learn more.</a></font>

</div>
<br><br>
</td>

